{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496971"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:00:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1448"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.19,0.47,0.2,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116311"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1448"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2236"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46849"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49904"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116311","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116311"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of chest pain and dyspnoea. During the triaging process, he suddenly collapses. His blood pressure is 90/43 mmHg, pulse 142/min, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 89% on air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is resuscitated with oxygen and a 500 mL fluid bolus, which improves his blood pressure (102/66 mmHg), SpO2 (99%), and level of consciousness. However, he still remains drowsy and intermittently responsive to commands and questioning. He is noted to have a parasternal heave on palpation of the precordium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe is now able to provide a further history, stating that his symptoms began four hours ago while resting at home following an elective arthroscopic knee washout two days prior. The chest pain is described as a 7/10 that is worse with breathing and feels as though he cannot catch his breath. He took esomeprazole for presumed reflux, but his symptoms did not improve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of hypertension on perindopril. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol socially. A CT pulmonary angiogram is performed (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IVC filter","Unfractionated heparin","Thrombolysis","Surgical catheter embolectomy","Rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the nature of the history of presenting complaint and the attached CT pulmonary angiogram demonstrating the presence of a saddle embolus, the working diagnosis in this case is a pulmonary embolus (Image).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for pulmonary embolus include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for deep vein thrombosis (Virchow\u0027s triad):\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEndothelial injury: Surgery (particularly orthopaedic), trauma, cellulitis, atherosclerosis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous stasis: Immobility (post-surgery), venous insufficiency, varicose veins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHypercoagulable state: Surgery, malignancy, pregnancy, factor V Leiden, oral contraceptive pill, inflammatory bowel disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESmoking, alcohol, age over 60 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical scenario is complicated by the patient\u0027s period of haemodynamic instability. In patients who are currently haemodynamically unstable, or who present with suspected PE complicated by haemodynamic instability that has been confirmed on CT pulmonary angiogram, the first-line treatment in this scenario is to administer \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E. This may be completed using alteplase 10 mg IV bolus over 1-2 minutes followed by a 90 mg IV infusion over two hours. Should the patient then show signs of clinical improvement, administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Eunfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E 10,000 units loading dose, followed by 18 units/kg/hr IV infusion is indicated. It should be be noted that consideration of bleeding risk with thrombolysis should always be considered before administration, particularly post-operatively however given this patient only had a knee arthroscopy, the risk of significant bleeding that cannot be easily managed is low. Should the patient have any absolute contraindications for thrombolytic therapy such as prior intracranial haemorrhage, known cerebral vascular lesion/pathology, ischaemic stroke within three months, suspected aortic dissection, or active bleeding, then \u003Cstrong\u003Esurgical catheter embolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E would have been the correct answer in this case. It is also indicated should thrombolytic therapy fail. Whilst having had a recent knee arthroscopy puts him at higher risk of haemorrhage at his surgical site, the patient is unstable and the risks of thrombolysis would outweigh the risks associated with a recent surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted that there is a reluctance in Australia to proceed to thrombolysis as first-line therapy, and hospital/health-service specific guidelines should be consulted. However, due to the presence of a large saddle embolus, a parasternal heave indicating right heart strain, and the patient not fully improving post bolus and resuscitation therapy, \u003Cstrong\u003Ethrombolysis\u003C/strong\u003E should be used over \u003Cstrong\u003Eunfractionated heparin\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is a direct oral anticoagulant (DOAC) indicated for the treatment of PE when the patient presents with haemodynamic stability or a picture not complicated by haemodynamic instability, as was the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst not discussed in the stem, an ECG would no doubt be performed as a part of the patient work-up, more than likely in the resuscitation setting as described above. However, the question is asking for the next step in management and given the acute nature of the presentation and recent collapse, the most immediate next step is to treat the underlying condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EIVC filter\u003C/strong\u003E would more than likely be considered in this patient by the treating team to prevent further PEs from peripheral venous origin. However, as the patient has an acute PE, this is not the correct option as it is not addressing the issue at hand.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with pulmonary embolus complicated by haemodynamic instability, thrombolytic therapy may be indicated"],"references":["Konstantinides SV, Torbicki A, Agnelli G, Danchin N, Fitzmaurice D, Gali\u00e8 N, Gibbs JS, Huisman MV, Humbert M, Kucher N, Lang I, Lankeit M, Lekakis J, Maack C, Mayer E, Meneveau N, Perrier A, Pruszczyk P, Rasmussen LH, Schindler TH, Svitil P, Vonk Noordegraaf A, Zamorano JL, Zompatori M; Task Force for the Diagnosis and Management of Acute Pulmonary Embolism of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC). 2014 ESC guidelines on the diagnosis and management of acute pulmonary embolism. Eur Heart J. 2014 Nov 14;35(43):3033-69, 3069a-3069k. doi: 10.1093/eurheartj/ehu283. Epub 2014 Aug 29. Erratum in: Eur Heart J. 2015 Oct 14;36(39):2666. Erratum in: Eur Heart J. 2015 Oct 14;36(39):2642. PMID: 25173341.","Schulman S, Konstantinides S, Hu Y, Tang LV. Venous thromboembolic diseases: diagnosis, management and thrombophilia testing: observations on NICE guideline [NG158]. Thrombosis and Haemostasis. 2020 Aug;120(08):1143-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19295"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22100"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19295"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d4a9ebba-2ca5-4cf9-919a-31de2c75ed68.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d4a9ebba-2ca5-4cf9-919a-31de2c75ed68.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":597,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22100"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fLAFbAZ8rFot6nPbcKtVyeZZnFnm2T.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fLAFbAZ8rFot6nPbcKtVyeZZnFnm2T.jpg","isProcessed":true